\subsection*{3.4. Leaf stomatal conductance ( $\mathrm{g}_{\mathrm{s}}$ )}

Salvia had the highest mean $g_{s}$ values, with the new Salvia treatment planted in 2013 having a similar mean $g_{s}$ to that of Salvia planted in 2012. Sedum had the lowest $g_{s}(p<0.001)$, with mean values differing by $249 \mathrm{mmol} \mathrm{m}^{-2} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ in 2012 and $185 \mathrm{mmol} \mathrm{m}^{-2} \mathrm{~s}^{-1}$ in 2013 from those of Salvia planted in 2012 (Figure 4). Due to time restrictions, the number of $\mathrm{g}_{\mathrm{s}}$ measurements executed in 2013 was substantially lower than in 2012, this might have contributed (along with differences in the stages of plant maturity or differences in the environmental conditions at the time of measuring) to most treatments having slightly lower mean $g_{s}$ values in 2013 than in 2012. Despite this, the order of magnitude of the mean $g_{s}$ for the five species has not changed between the two years (Figure 4).

