\subsection*{3.5. Surface temperature ( $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ ) and outgoing long-wave radiation ( $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ )}
$\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and related $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ in 2012 and 2013 are presented in Figure 5 (showing days with $\mathrm{T}_{\max }>24^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, when the differences in $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ were greatest). During the day, particularly between 12:00-16:00 h , plots with Salvia or Stachys had the lowest $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$, and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$, whereas plots with Sempervivum or bare substrate had the highest ( $\mathrm{p}>0.001$ ); differences between mean values during that period reached up to $10^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $12 \%$ (or $\sim 65 \mathrm{~W} \mathrm{~m}^{-2}$ ) for $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$, respectively. Values for $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$, and related values for $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$, of purple Heuchera and Sedum were generally in-between the values of the other four treatments. The differences between mean $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ for purple Heuchera or Sedum plots and those with Salvia reached up to $5^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $6 \%$ (or $\sim 30 \mathrm{~W} \mathrm{~m}^{-2}$ ), respectively. In 2012, $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ values for yellow Heuchera plots were similar to those obtained for Salvia and Stachys plots (Figures 5a and c). In contrast, in 2013 after the loss of many of the yellow Heuchera plants, mean $\mathrm{T}_{\mathrm{s}}$ and $\mathrm{L}_{\mathrm{o}}$ in yellow Heuchera plots between 12:00-16:00 h were up by $4^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ and $5 \%$ (or $\sim 25 \mathrm{~W} \mathrm{~m}^{-2}$ ), respectively, compared to plots with Salvia and Stachys (Figures 5b and d).

